The FRED data for this question are from the IMF. Click on the "Primary Commodity Prices" link from the FRED page, and you get to an IMF page. From the IMF page, click on the link labeled, "By commodity, in terms of US$, market prices 1/". That takes you to a file with data and information about the data. The data exactly match the FRED page. Here's the information about the wheat data: "U.S. No. 1 hard red winter, ordinary protein, Kansas City $/MT (USDA, Grain and Feed Market News, Washington, DC) 1/" with a footnote: "1/ Average of daily quotations." The best source for this data I have found to be the High Plains Journal: https://www.hpj.com/search/?l=25&s=start_time&sd=desc&f=html&t=article%2Cvideo%2Cyoutube%2Ccollection&app=editorial&nsa=eedition&q=Kansas+City+wheat+prices

Have y'all seen what's happening to fertilizer prices? It's collateral damage of the energy crisis in China. Fertilizer producers in China are struggling to meet demand, and separately, urea production has been cut. Urea is a component of most fertilizers, including types used for wheat; urea is the most important source of nitrogen in commercially available fertilizers (and is used as fertilizer itself). I can't imagine urea and fertilizer prices won't have an impact on wheat prices. https://twitter.com/JavierBlas/status/1453746602552737797 https://www.reuters.com/world/china/china-seeking-resolve-issues-caused-by-power-curbs-higher-raw-materials-prices-2021-09-24/ https://extension.umn.edu/nutrient-management/nitrogen https://blog-crop-news.extension.umn.edu/2021/10/with-high-fertilizer-prices-should-you.html

Yesterday, I thought the Sept value would be approx $268/MT (+/-4), and it's $269.74. Down $5.14/MT from Aug. As I've said many times before, the volatility is very high, so it's hard to make a tight forecast. This YTD, out of 9 months so far, prices have swung by ~$10/MT 2 months, ~$20/MT one month, ~$30/MT another month, and ~$40/MT 2 months. For only 3 months in 2021 has the swing been substantially <$10/MT. I still see the trend as being generally up. Based on Oct 1 through 16, I expect growth to be in the <$10/MT (+/-5) range for Oct. over Sept; I expect Oct's value to be ~$275 to $285/MT. From there, I'd expect about a 55% chance of staying in bin 3, with a greater chance of bin 4 than bin 2.

The IMF publishes the average price of U.S. No. 1 hard red winter Wheat (ordinary protein) over each month. The Sep 21 future in this product is trading at 585 while the Dec 21 future trades at 597 (cents per bushel). We interpolate between these prices to infer the Nov price as 593, and take this to be representative of the average price over all days in November. Then we convert from cents per bushel to get $217.88 per metric ton. We made many approximations so our confidence intervals are wide for this estimate.

1) The megadrought in the western U.S. doesn't appear to overlap with where wheat is grown. 2) I don't think COVID has really had an effect on Punjab (India's dominant wheat growing region). 3) I think that with the U.S. reaching herd immunity, big pharma will quickly trade vaccines for Canadian and western European dollars. 4) I'm not even attempting to analyze Chinese figures (because they're probably fiction anyway). 5) I DO think we're going to have 10-20% food price inflation though, but that's because of diminution in the value of the dollar (not supply scarcity).

Just over 2/3 of all wheat is produced by China, India, Russia, the US, Canada, and Australia, in that order. China's crop is forecast to be good this year, and their imports are expected to drop a little, which will ease prices. India is expected to have a bumper crop and will likely increase exports. Russia is expected to decrease exports because of export restrictions and lower production forecasts. In the US, people have been forecasting a record year for exports, but there are some drought concerns in several states. Wheat exports are forecast to be down a bit, though, because of rising exports from other countries and uncompetitive prices. Canada's production is expected to fall for 2021-2022, as is Australia's. (Also, Australia is in the midst of its worst mouse plague in at least decades, and many farmers are having to burn their crops because of it. If you haven't seen anything about this yet, Google "mice Australia" for horror movies and pictures. It is beyond your worst nightmares.)

Fundamentally global wheat is robust, but it being pushed higher with the rising basket of commodities that are structurally weak/bullish. The latest June WASDE report projects 2021/22 season-average farm price unchanged at $6.50 per bushel. Dollar weakness, supply chain constraints, elevated freight costs should keep wheat range bound.
